(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 9 :title "Chapter 9 — Environments" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/09-environments.md" :size 2621 :sha256 "af7d854cb1e2c78f" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-09\ntitle: Environments\nbook: reference\nchapter: 9\nof: 16\npart: I\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane Q9)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\nprev: 08-continuations\nnext: 10-a-tiny-compiler\n---\n\n# Chapter 9 — Environments\n\nAn environment is the machinery that maps names to values. Every closure carries one; every lookup walks one.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Environments are what make scope work. Local vs global, lexical vs dynamic — those are all statements about *which environment gets looked up.*\n\n## The frame\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-frame bindings) (list 'frame bindings))\n(define f (make-frame '((x 10) (y 20))))\n(display f) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(frame ((x 10) (y 20)))\n```\n\n## The environment as a chain of frames\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-env frame parent) (list 'env frame parent))\n\n(define e0 (make-env (make-frame '((x 10))) 'no-parent))\n(define e1 (make-env (make-frame '((y 20))) e0))\n\n(display e0) (newline)\n(display e1) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(env (frame ((x 10))) no-parent)\n(env (frame ((y 20))) (env (frame ((x 10))) no-parent))\n```\n\n## Lookup walks the chain\n\n```scheme\n(define (lookup name env)\n  (cond\n    ((eq? env 'no-parent) 'unbound)\n    (else\n     (let ((hit (assoc name (cadr (list-ref env 1)))))\n       (if hit\n           (cadr hit)\n           (lookup name (list-ref env 2)))))))\n\n(display (lookup 'y e1)) (newline)\n(display (lookup 'x e1)) (newline)\n(display (lookup 'z e1)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n20\n10\nunbound\n```\n\n## Extending\n\n```scheme\n(define (extend-env env new-bindings)\n  (make-env (make-frame new-bindings) env))\n\n(define e2 (extend-env e1 '((z 30))))\n(display (lookup 'z e2)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n30\n```\n\n## Closures capture the environment\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-closure params body env)\n  (list 'closure params body env))\n\n(define c (make-closure '(x) '(+ x 10) e1))\n(display c) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(closure (x) (+ x 10) (env (frame ((y 20))) (env (frame ((x 10))) no-parent)))\n```\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Environments are chains of frames.\n- Lookup walks the chain until it finds the name.\n- Extension adds a new frame at the top.\n- Closures capture the environment at their definition point.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\n```scheme\n(display (list 'env '(frame ((x 1))) 'no-parent)) (newline)\n```\n\nIf you can chain frames, you're ready for a tiny compiler.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-6]] — metacircular.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-8]] — continuations.\n- [[book-of-one-shot#chapter-9]] — one-shot-and-composition.\n")
